(1, 'An inspiration - Lizzie Vel&aacute;squez', 'How does it feel when you are touted as the ugliest person on the planet? You feel it''s the end of the world when your photos and videos go viral on the internet with people pouring in their hate comments over your distorted looks and figure.\n\nThat''s exactly what happened to Lizzie Vel&aacute;squez, a 26 year old girl from Austin, Texas, who suffers from a rare congenital disease that impedes her body from accumulating fat. Till date, she hasn''t weighed more than 29 kg and is blind in the right eye. Few years back, some nuisance creators posted a 8 second video of hers on internet and the video immediately went viral garnering her comments full of hate and disgust. In some of the YouTube comments, she was even referred to as ''it'' and a ''monster'' while others encouraged her to commit suicide.  \n\nThat incident left a deep scar on her mind and soul and after being sunk in misery for days, she decided to redefine the word ''ugly''. She did not let the world define her fate on the basis of her external appearance. Instead she pushed herself forward and set life-changing goals for her. Since then, she has authored three best-selling books that have garnered worldwide attention. She graduated from Texas State University with a degree in Communication Studies in the year 2012. Her positive attitude towards life also landed her an opportunity to deliver motivation talk at TED event - "How do YOU define yourself" - a video that has hit millions of views since it was first published on YouTube. \n\nToday, she''s an active motivational speaker, has delivered talks over 200 conferences and rigorously campaigns against bullying.  In her own words -"I didn''t sink down to their level. Instead, I got my revenge through my accomplishments and determination. In the battle between the ''World''s Ugliest Woman'' video vs. me, I think I won."', '2016-02-13 12:13:17'),
(2, 'The Woman With Super Vision - Concetta Antico', 'A human eye can normally distinguish one million different shades of color. But there are some exceptionally gifted people who can distinguish 100 times more colors than an ordinary human eye can perceive. Tetrachromacy is a condition that is caued due to the presence of four types of cone cells in the eye. Cone cells are those that are responsible for providing color vision to humans. An ordinary human eye contains only three types of cone cells in the retina but certain rare individuals are born with four types and are referred to as tetrachromats. \r\n\r\nOne such confirmed tetrachromat is Concetta Antico, an Australian artist who is believed to have super human vision and can distinguish 100 million shades of color that are identical or invisible to ordinary humans beings. The extra receptors in her eye enable her to distinguish vivid shades of color that an ordinary human eye cannot comprehend. She mentions that she can see red color on the edge of a green leaf and a dull grey colored stone appears to her like a shimmering mixture of orange, yellow, green, pink and blue. \r\n\r\nAntico is a professional artist and has been teaching art for over 20 years. She also owns an art gallery in San Diego, California where she uses her enhanced vision to create paintings bursting with vibrant color. She shows her world to the people through her paintings. She was surprised when she learnt that other humans see so little color in real life. She further elaborates - "My natural visual world is breathtaking. The world is so vibrant and stimulating to my eyes, allowing me to paint what I see, what I love the most, and what I live. The beauty I surround myself with is my daily muse."  \r\n\r\nHowever, she also complains that enhanced vision is not always a blessing. Her extreme sensitivity to colors is baffling to people around  her, for instance, while shopping she finds it  difficult to match clothes as she sees more clashing shades of color - something others do not seem to notice. The store appears like a trash pile of color as she sees a different color beaming from every angle. White is her favorite color because it is less hurting and more peaceful to the eye. \r\n\r\nAlthough Antico was born with an incredible genetic gift, her daughter happens to be color-blind - the cause of which has been established to be genetic mutation. Antico has been the subject of study for many scientists and researchers trying to get into depth of tetrachromacy. Antico contributes and participates regularly in scientific experiments with a hope of finding a cure for people suffering from color-blindness similar to her daughter. Her another mission in life is to teach art to less fortunate ones and to launch an online platform to help people discover if they are tetrachromats. ', '2016-02-16 10:56:07');

