('569e567b101d6', 72, 81, '&lt;div&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;author-advanced&quot;&gt;Imagine a life without electricity â€“ a life paralyzed due to absence of the current that runs in wires and lights up our houses and warms our homes. A day without electricity has the capacity to bring everything to a standstill with no banking, no transport and virtually no governance.&amp;nbsp; And this increasing dependence on electricity to make our life easier brings out the necessity to innovate new methods of producing the same. The reservoirs of oils and gas are depleting and soon world would have to find cleaner and greener ways of continuing with the way of life people have become accustomed to. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;author-advanced&quot;&gt;The passion towards circuits and the intriguing concept of energy and power go back to my 10th grade when for the very first time I worked on a science project to generate electricity from potatoes using copper and zinc electrodes, multi-meter and a light emitting diode. I still remember how fascinated and intrigued I was to see the LED glow, powered by nothing more than a bunch of potatoes. And from there on started my deep respect for circuits, currents and everything included therein. If I loved mathematics and physics before, I adored the subjects after. Nothing could satiate my curiosity and the more I learnt, the more inclined I was to further understand and learn about the same. Intellectually inclined and analytically strong, I was soon able to gain expertise within the subjects. The same love and passion for the subjects saw me scoring the high of 95% in Mathematics and 86% in Physics in my 12th boards. I was even awarded a certificate of merit in my 11thgrade in Mathematics and participated successfully in Nation Level Science Talent Search Examination as well as Science Olympiads. By the end of my school, I knew that my elixir was Electrical Engineering and putting in hard work and dedication saw me securing a seat in the one of the best colleges of our state â€“ Sri Jayachamarajendra College of Engineering, Mysore.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;author-advanced&quot;&gt;Moving on to engineering, I felt a paradigm shift in my personality. Though I had always been an outgoing person and constantly participated in various debates, dance and other activities in school, my years spent at my under-graduation college molded my personality, turning me into more of a practical person. I found myself delving deep into the theories of the subjects and deeper still into the implementation of what I had learnt. Experimenting with the technology available, spending hours together in the labs, I felt my respect for the subject grow further. I was extremely enchanted by subjects such as Communication Engineering, Power Electronics, Network Theory and Power Systems, which further strengthened my resolve to be associated with the Power Sector. My third year undergraduate study course â€œPower Station Practiceâ€ in which I studied the generation of Electrical Energy and the training at National Thermal Power Corporation where I assimilated the basics of generation, distribution and transmission of electrical power and the effect of corona and transients on power system helped me further understand the operations, the challenges and the entire mechanics of the process. My analytical skills and mathematical skills assisted my development further and saw me gaining expertise in subjects such as Power System Analysis and topics such as Laplace and Fourier theorems. Moving on to final year project, I got the excellent opportunity to work under the guidance of Dr. Mira Nair. True to my passion for renewable sources of energy, I worked on a project titled â€“ â€œReinventing the Solar Power Satelliteâ€œ, in which I studied about the economic and functional design of Solar Power Satellite to convert sunlight to electricity and transfer the electricity wirelessly to various regions of Earth and also implemented the same by means of a working model. While the project required extensive research in the form of studying the entire process, it also included redesigning of solar power satellite by integrating solar arrays and microwave transmitters on opposite side of the slab which would result in narrower beam and hence reduced size of the rectenna and the overall system. The aim was to make solar power satellite economically feasible and to generate maximum power at peak hours. My work was highly applauded and appreciated. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;author-advanced&quot;&gt;I have now been working with Indiaâ€™s premier IT Company â€“ TCS for just over an year. The experience has been scintillating so far and has further helped me understand cooperates, acclimatize myself to the high hours of work and evolve as a team player. It has also prepared me for the rigors of another academic program for it has given me renewed focus and motivation to do my bit. I now aspire to further my career within the Electrical Engineering domain and work for an International Power Generation Company. To reach the desired position and industry, I require further training within the subject and I could fathom no better university to provide me the same. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;', 'Please review my essay for grammatical errors mistakes and advise how it can be improved further. Please check if something need to be added or deleted from the existing essay.', 'MS in Electrical Engineering from University of California, Los Angeles\nMS in Electrical Engineering from University of Texas, Austin', 1),
